In article <1993Aug24.103544.7398@lfmcal.cuc.ab.ca>, lloyd@lfmcal.cuc.ab.ca (Lloyd Miller) writes...
>Tim Smith (tzs@hardy.u.washington.edu) wrote:
>> I've seen procedures for logically flipping a coin by phone.  They tend
>> to be complicated.  What's wrong with the following one?
> 
>> 	1. Party A generates large primes p and q, with p = 1 mod 4,
>> 	and q = 3 mod 4.
> 
>> 	2. Party A tells party B pq.
> 
>> 	3. Party B picks one of the following two statements and makes it
>> 	to A:
> 
>> 		"I call heads iff p > q"
>> 	or
> 
>> 		"I call tails iff p > q"
> 
>Party A can cheat at this point by simply switching p and q.

P = 3 (mod 4) and Q = 1 (mod 4).  If P and Q were switched they wouldn't fit
this.  For example, say P was 19, and Q was 15.  If he said Q was 15, then
party B would know that Q mod 4 was not 1.
